<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0275 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2056EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u w BC-HouseDisclosures-SouthCarolina     05-25 0471</FIRST><SECOND>BC-House Disclosures-South Carolina,570</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here are capsule summaries of the financialdisclosure forms filed by members of the House from South Carolinafor 1987 and released Wednesday.   Income includes the House salary, honoraria earnings fromwriting and speeches and other income such as dividends andinterest.   Earnings by the representatives' spouses and dependents are notincluded in the income figure.   The asset and liability figures for the representatives do notinclude holdings and liabilities of spouses and dependents.   Representatives are permitted to keep honoraria earnings fromspeeches and writings up to 30 percent of their salary. For nearlyall members, their salary was $89,500 at the end of 1987. Thespeaker of the House was paid at the annualized rate of $115,000and the Democratic and Republican leaders were paid at theannualized rate of $99,500.   Many members receive honoraria above the limit and donate theexcess to charity.   In their financial disclosure forms, representatives are allowedto list income, assets and liabilities by ranges instead ofspecific figures. However, some representatives provide specificfigures.   In their listing of assets, representatives do not have toinclude their personal residences and vehicles. Gifts, thoughlisted, are not counted in income figure given here.</TEXT><TEXT>   ROBIN TALLON   Income: $155,289-$240,784.   Honoraria: $13,500, None.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $715,003 and up-$1.05 million and up.   Liabilities: $235,004-$605,000.   Tallon heavily invests and trades in stocks and properties. Hehas received numerous trips in conjunction with speakingengagements and even gave a speech at the Leonard, Call TaylorCongressional Classic Tennis tournament in which he participated.</TEXT><TEXT>   ELIZABETH PATTERSON   Income: $112,293-$135,289.   Honoraria: $8,500, none given to charity.   Gifts: Furniture to spouse and all expense paid trip to S.C.Bankers   Convention.   Assets: $120,001-$305,000.   Liabilities: $15,001-$50,000.   Patterson's husband and children hold additional assets totalingbetween $450,000 and $715,000 and up.</TEXT><TEXT>   JOHN M. SPRATT Jr.   Income: $246,599-$466,083.   Honoraria: $4,300, all given to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $1.75 million-$2 million and up.   Liabilities: $35,001-$115,000.   Spratt receives funds from property rental, interest anddividends. One of Spratt's dependent children, Catherine, hasassets in a trust fund valued between $1.19 million-$1.38 millionand up.</TEXT><TEXT>   ARTHUR RAVENEL Jr.   Income: $112,990-$167,983.   Honoraria: None.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $695,007-$995,000.   Liabilities: None.</TEXT><TEXT>   BUTLER C. DERRICK Jr.   Income: $127,735-$132,733.   Honoraria: $36,750, $10.865.01 given to charity.   Gifts: None.   Assets: $505,004-$870,000 and up.   Liabilities: $165,004-$350,000.   Most of Derrick's assets are real estate. He accepted 24speaking fees during the year. He reported accepting reimbursementfor 10 trips, including three to Florida and two to the VirginIslands. Among the corporations and lobbying associations whichpaid for the trips were: American Apparel Manufacturers, AtlanticApparel Contractors, Burlington Industries, Connell Rice and SugarCo., Florida Sugar Cane League, U.S. Telephone Co., Time Inc., andMONEY magazine.</TEXT><TEXT>   FLOYD SPENCE   Spence was given a filing extension until May 31.</TEXT></DOC>